nstead, Surrey, England":"Banstead, Surrey, Anglie, United Kingdom","Banstead, Surrey, England":"Banstead, Surrey, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"Abt 1380–":"omkring 1380–Afdød","1380–1432":"1380–1432","1380–Male":"1380–Afdød","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1389–Female":"1389–Afdød","1408–Male":"1408–Afdød","1340–1420":"1340–1420","1345–1389":"1345–1389","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","ABT 1377":"omkring 1377","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","Abt 1380":"omkring 1380","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","Of, Banstead, Surrey, England":"Banstead, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Banstead, Surrey, England":"Banstead, Surrey, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1380–":"circa 1380–Overleden","1380–1432":"1380–1432","1380–Male":"1380–Overleden","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1389–Female":"1389–Overleden","1408–Male":"1408–Overleden","1340–1420":"1340–1420","1345–1389":"1345–1389","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","ABT 1377":"circa 1377","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","Abt 1380":"circa 1380","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","Of, Banstead, Surrey, England":"Banstead, Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Banstead, Surrey, England":"Banstead, Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1380–":"about 1380–Deceased","1380–1432":"1380–1432","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1389–Female":"1389–Deceased","1408–Male":"1408–Deceased","1340–1420":"1340–1420","1345–1389":"1345–1389","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","ABT 1377":"about 1377","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","Abt 1380":"about 1380","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","Of, Banstead, Surrey, England":"Banstead, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Banstead, Surrey, England":"Banstead, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lambert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, French, Walloon, Dutch, German, Polish, Czech, and Slovak: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. In England, the native Old English form <i>Landbeorht</i> was replaced by <i>Lambert</i>, the Continental form of the name that was taken to England by the Normans from France. The name gained wider currency in Britain in the Middle Ages with the immigration of weavers from Flanders, among whom Saint Lambert or Lamprecht, bishop of Maastricht in around 700, was a popular cult figure. In Italy the name was popularized in the Middle Ages as a result of the fame of Lambert I and II, Dukes of Spoleto and Holy Roman Emperors. <i>Lambert</i> is the second most frequent surname in Wallonia. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Slovenian <b>Lampret</b> and <b>Lampreht</b> (see also   Lampert  ).","History: Aubin Lambert <i>dit</i> Champagne from Tourouvre in Orne, France, married Élisabeth Aubert in Quebec City, QC, in 1670; see also   Champagne  . Eustache Lambert from Boulogne-sur-Mer in Pas-de-Calais, France, married Marie Laurence in France <i>c.</i> 1656, died in Quebec City, QC, in 1673. Pierre Lambert from Fourmetot in Eure, France, married Marie Normand in Quebec City, QC, in 1680. Augustin Hébert <i>dit</i> Lambert, a descendant of Augustin Hébert from Paris, France, married Françoise Petit in Varennes, QC, in 1761. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Lambers","meanings":["Dutch: patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lamberth","meanings":["English: variant of   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lambertus","meanings":["German and Dutch: humanistic name, Latinized form of the personal name   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lamberti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Carlo, Gaetano, Luciano, Amedeo, Angelo, Biagio, Domenic, Donato, Enrico, Gino, Iolanda.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Lamberto</i>, an equivalent of   Lambert  . This surname is also found in Corsica and southern France.","German and Dutch: Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  , using the genitive of its Latinized form   Lambertus  ."]},{"name":"Lamberty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Ana, Dimas, Jose, Juan, Altagracia, Angel, Blanca, Efrain, Fernando, Jaime, Ramon.","German and French: Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  , from <i>Lamberti</i>, the genitive of its Latinized form   Lambertus  . Compare   Lamberti   2."]},{"name":"Lambertz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heinz, Erna, Johann, Ralf.","North German: patronymic from   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lamberto","meanings":["Italian and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Lamberto</i> (see   Lambert  )."]},{"name":"Lampert","meanings":["English, North German, Dutch, and Slovak; Hungarian (<b>Lampért</b>): variant of   Lambert  . In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed some cognates from other languages, for example Slovenian <b>Lampret</b> and <b>Lampreht</b>.","English: variant of <b>Lambard</b>, an occupational name from Middle English <i>lambherd</i>, <i>lambhird</i>, <i>lambhurd</i> ‘lamb-herd’ (Old English <i>lamb</i> + <i>hierde</i>)."]},{"name":"Lambertsen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik.","Dutch, Danish, North German, and Norwegian: patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  . This surname has died out in the Netherlands.","History: Cornelius Lambertsen came from Utrecht, the Netherlands, arriving at New Amsterdam in New Netherland (now New York City, NY) in 1642."]},{"name":"Lamb","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Lamb</i>, a pet form of   Lambert  .","English: nickname for a meek and inoffensive person, from Middle English <i>lamb</i>, or a metonymic occupational name for a keeper of lambs. See also   Lamm  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luain</b> ‘descendant of the warrior’, formerly Anglicized as <b>O'Loan</b> (see   Lane   3). MacLysaght comments: \"The form <b>Lamb(e)</b>, which results from a more than usually absurd pseudo-translation (<i>uan</i> ‘lamb’), is now much more numerous than <i>O'Loan</i> itself.\"."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Lambert was born about 1380, in Banstead, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ralph Lambert, was 42 and his mother, Julia Ellinbrygge, was 36. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1380–":"umbes 1380–Surnud","1380–1432":"1380–1432","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1389–Female":"1389–Surnud","1408–Male":"1408–Surnud","1340–1420":"1340–1420","1345–1389":"1345–1389","1345":"1345","1389":"1389","1432":"1432","1420":"1420","ABT 1377":"umbes 1377","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","Abt 1380":"umbes 1380","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","Of, Banstead, Surrey, England":"Banstead, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Banstead, Surrey, England":"Banstead, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1380–":"noin 1380–Kuollut","1380–1432":"1380–1432","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1385–1420":"